!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>HOS Cultivation</title>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">

  <style>
    :root {
      --green: #2f5a28;
      --green-light: #e9f4e6;
      --text: #222;
      --muted: #666;
      --bg: #fafafa;
      --radius: 12px;
    }

    body {
      margin: 0;
      font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
      background: var(--bg);
      color: var(--text);
      line-height: 1.6;
    }

    header {
      padding: 3rem 1.5rem;
      text-align: center;
      background: white;
      border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;
    }

    header h1 {
      margin: 0;
      font-size: 2.4rem;
      color: var(--green);
      font-weight: 700;
    }

    main {
      max-width: 900px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: 2rem 1.5rem;
    }

    h2 {
      margin-top: 3rem;
      color: var(--green);
      font-size: 1.8rem;
    }

    .notice {
      background: var(--green-light);
      border-left: 4px solid var(--green);
      padding: 1rem 1.2rem;
      border-radius: var(--radius);
      margin: 2rem 0;
    }

    /* Collapsible sections */
    details {
      background: white;
      border-radius: var(--radius);
      border: 1px solid #eee;
      margin: 1rem 0;
      overflow: hidden;
      box-shadow: 0 1px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.04);
    }

    summary {
      cursor: pointer;
      padding: 1.2rem 1.5rem;
      list-style: none;
      font-size: 1.2rem;
      color: var(--green);
      font-weight: 600;
      display: flex;
      justify-content: space-between;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 1rem;
    }

    summary::-webkit-details-marker {
      display: none;
    }

    /* SVG chevron */
    .chevron {
      width: 1.2rem;
      height: 1.2rem;
      flex-shrink: 0;
      transition: transform 0.25s ease;
      color: var(--green);
    }

    details[open] .chevron {
      transform: rotate(180deg);
    }

    /* Slide animation */
    details .content {
      max-height: 0;
      overflow: hidden;
      padding: 0 1.5rem;
      transition: max-height 0.35s ease, padding 0.35s ease;
    }

    details[open] .content {
      max-height: 2000px;
      padding: 1rem 1.5rem 1.5rem;
    }

    footer {
      text-align: center;
      padding: 2rem 1rem;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
      color: var(--muted);
    }

    a {
      color: var(--green);
      text-decoration: none;
    }
    a:hover {
      text-decoration: underline;
    }
  </style>
</head>

<body>

<header>
  <h1>Cultivation</h1>
  <p>Guidance, resources and practical methods for growing hardy orchids.</p>
</header>

<main>

  <section>
    <h2>Resources for Members</h2>

    <p><a href="#">Seed Bank List (members only)</a></p>
    <p><a href="#">Consumable Items (members only)</a></p>
    <p>Use contact details in JHOS to contact the Seed Bank Manager.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Workshops & Events</h2>

    <details>
      <summary>
        <span>Seed Sowing Workshops</span>
        <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="content">
        <p>
          One‑day workshops covering all aspects of seed sowing and aftercare of both summer and
          winter‑green orchids. Tutor: John Haggar.
        </p>

        <h3>Seed Sowing Workshop 2026</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>Sunday 23rd August 2026</strong><br>
          9.30am – 4.00pm<br>
          Hagbourne Village Hall, East Hagbourne, Didcot, OX11 9LR
        </p>

        <p><a href="#">Booking Form & Details</a></p>

        <div class="notice">
          Only current members may take part.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Symbiotic Seed Germination Fungi</h2>

    <details>
      <summary>
        <span>Overview</span>
        <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="content">
        <p>
          Symbiotic fungi are grown in Petri dishes containing agar, vitamin B extract and rolled
          sieved oats. These fungi infect orchid seeds and enable germination.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Society maintains three isolates proven to germinate a range of terrestrial orchids.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        <span>Fungal Isolates (B1, A36, Q414)</span>
        <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="content">
        <h3>B1</h3>
        <p>A vigorous all‑rounder suitable for beginners. Proven with many Anacamptis, Dactylorhiza, Goodyera, Gymnadenia, Habanaria, Orchis, Platanthera, Ponerorchis, Pterostylis, Serapias and Spiranthes species.</p>

        <h3>A36</h3>
        <p>Fast‑growing all‑rounder. Proven with Gymnadenia, Anacamptis papilionacea, A. elegans, Dactylorhiza and Spiranthes.</p>

        <h3>Q414</h3>
        <p>Slower‑growing isolate. Proven with Serapias, Dactylorhiza, Spiranthes and some Anacamptis.</p>

        <p>Members are encouraged to report additional successes to the Seed Bank Manager.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Donating Orchid Seed</h2>

    <details>
      <summary>
        <span>Requirements & Permissions</span>
        <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="content">
        <p>
          Donations must be legally obtained. Seed from wild plants requires written landowner
          permission. Schedule 8 species require Natural England (or equivalent) approval.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        <span>Harvesting, Cleaning & Drying</span>
        <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="content">
        <p>
          Harvest on a dry day just before capsule splitting. Clean seed using a tea strainer and
          store in paper envelopes.
        </p>
        <p>
          Dry seed immediately using dried rice in an airtight jar for 2–3 days before posting.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        <span>Posting & Identification</span>
        <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="content">
        <p>
          Seeds must be sent in crush‑proof containers. Include photographs of the parent plant
          for identification.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Propagation from Seed</h2>

    <details>
      <summary>
        <span>Why Orchid Seed Needs Help</span>
        <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="content">
        <p>
          Orchid seeds are extremely small and lack stored nutrients. In nature they rely on
          infection by beneficial fungi to germinate.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        <span>Seed Sowing at Home</span>
        <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="content">
        <p>
          Many members sow seed at home using improvised sterile environments. Key requirements:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Sterile workspace (glove box or similar)</li>
          <li>Pressure cooker for sterilisation</li>
          <li>Agar‑based media (with or without fungi)</li>
          <li>Jars, Petri dishes, tools and chemicals</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        <span>Basic Method</span>
        <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="content">
        <ol>
          <li>Soak seed in sugar solution for 4 days.</li>
          <li>Wash three times in sterile water.</li>
          <li>Sterilise in diluted bleach for 10–30 minutes.</li>
          <li>Wash again and sow onto medium.</li>
          <li>Add fungus (if used) and keep in the dark.</li>
          <li>Replate protocorms when large enough.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Cultivation Guidance</h2>

    <details>
      <summary>
        <span>General Principles</span>
        <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="content">
        <p>
          The Society brings together experts on propagation and cultivation. Mimicking natural
          habitats is key to success.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        <span>Orchids for the Garden</span>
        <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="content">
        <p>
          Suitable genera include Dactylorhiza, Epipactis and Orchis. Grow in open compost, avoid
          summer drought, and provide shade on hot days.
        </p>
        <p><a href="#">Useful article by Malcolm Brownsword</a></p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        <span>Cold Frame / Cold Greenhouse</span>
        <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="content">
        <p>
          Mediterranean winter‑green orchids benefit from frost‑free conditions using a simple
          thermostatically controlled heater.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        <span>Further Information</span>
        <svg class="chevron" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
        </svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="content">
        <p>
          Join the Society, attend meetings, and explore the extensive cultivation articles in
          the HOS Journal/Newsletter.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

  </section>

</main>

<footer>
  For enquiries, please refer to contact details in JHOS.
</footer>

</body>
</html>
